<br>
The answer is: Yes, they do.  Not so much for bandwidth issues but for the fact that the average joe who tries to set one up ends up messing up its security and it (the rogue server) starts to spam the entire network and spreading virii.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 2. If they do allow it, is it even slightly feasable if they don't assign a static IP? In Theory, your IP lease shouldn't expire if your machine is online most of the time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Answer:  Yes, it is possible.  There are services that will auto-reference your dynamic IP address via some other reference.  Your computer registers with it periodically.  I've never used them and don't know how reliable they are.   Regardless, I doubt that a residential account would allow you to set up the server anyway.<br>
<br>
[quote3. Who do you contact to register a domain name, and what does it cost?[/quote]<br>
