<br>
I called the local telephone company to set up phone service to my new home, and they informed me that they now offer DSL service. According to the lady that I talked to, and she may or may not be 100% correct on all of this.<br>
<br>
They provide a static IP<br>
<br>
They will allow a web server<br>
<br>
They will register your web server in their DNS server for a healthy fee.<br>
<br>
No setup fee, they give me the DSL modem, and the cost is $29.95 per month for the first year, and $49.95 thereafter.<br>
<br>
I know exactly what your saying about Microshaft products, especially Outlook and Exchange. My only good reason for even considering setting up an exchange server is to gain the experience in having done it to make passing the MCSE test a bit easier. As far as general security goes, the following are excellent ideas for starting out with a Microsoft server.<br>
<br>
1. rename and disable the guest account. <br>
2. rename both the admin account and admin group.<br>
3. stop the default admin shares (yes, this can be done permanently)<br>
4. give the &quot;everyone&quot;group list access instead of the default full control.<br>
5. have an antivirus utility installed<br>
6. enable security auditing<br>
<br>
